ange, and the search for alternative forms of energy, nuclear power continues to affect the lives of communities around the world. In Nuclear Portraits, scholars from Europe, North America, and Asia demonstrate the complexity, controversy, contradictions, and dangers that surround many aspects of the nuclear industry. The resulting local, regional, national, and international concerns that arise, such as the disasters at Chernobyl and Fukushima, call into question the optimism espoused by the nuclear industry. We live in a world with more nuclear nations than ever before and energy policy is central to the mounting global concern about climate change. The innovative essays found in Nuclear Portraits will open your eyes to the realities of nuclear energy, thereby allowing you to decide for yourself whose side you are on.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aNuclear industryxEnvironmental aspects. 0aNuclear industryxGovernment policy. 0aNuclear industryxSocial aspects. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aBauer, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, David Elijah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Marissa Zappora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldman, James W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenberg, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJobin, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKalmbach, Karena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKasperski, Tatiana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKosson, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacDowell, Laurel Sefton